{"content":"---\ntitle: \"How to: Create a Line Using a LineGeometry\"\nms.date: \"03/30/2017\"\ndev_langs: \n  - \"csharp\"\n  - \"vb\"\nhelpviewer_keywords: \n  - \"graphics [WPF], lines\"\nms.assetid: 41231b22-1f74-4c26-a8e7-a55b29f8f6bd\n---\n# How to: Create a Line Using a LineGeometry\nThis example shows how to use the <xref:System.Windows.Media.LineGeometry> class to describe a line. A <xref:System.Windows.Media.LineGeometry> is defined by its start and end points.  \n  \n## Example  \n The following example shows how to create and render a <xref:System.Windows.Media.LineGeometry>.  A <xref:System.Windows.Shapes.Path> element is used to render the line.  Since a line has no area, the <xref:System.Windows.Shapes.Path> object's <xref:System.Windows.Shapes.Shape.Fill%2A> is not specified; instead the <xref:System.Windows.Shapes.Shape.Stroke%2A> and <xref:System.Windows.Shapes.Shape.StrokeThickness%2A> properties are used.  \n  \n [!code-xaml[GeometryOverviewSamples_snip#GraphicsMMLineGeometryExample](~/samples/snippets/csharp/VS_Snippets_Wpf/GeometryOverviewSamples_snip/CS/GeometryExamples.xaml#graphicsmmlinegeometryexample)]  \n  \n [!code-csharp[GeometryOverviewSamples_procedural_snip#GraphicsMMLineGeometryExample](~/samples/snippets/csharp/VS_Snippets_Wpf/GeometryOverviewSamples_procedural_snip/CSharp/GeometryExamples.cs#graphicsmmlinegeometryexample)]\n [!code-vb[GeometryOverviewSamples_procedural_snip#GraphicsMMLineGeometryExample](~/samples/snippets/visualbasic/VS_Snippets_Wpf/GeometryOverviewSamples_procedural_snip/visualbasic/geometryexamples.vb#graphicsmmlinegeometryexample)]  \n  \n ![A LineGeometry](./media/graphicsmm-line.gif \"graphicsmm_line\")  \nA LineGeometry drawn from (10,20) to (100,130)  \n  \n Other simple geometry classes include <xref:System.Windows.Media.LineGeometry> and <xref:System.Windows.Media.EllipseGeometry>. These geometries, as well as more complex ones, can also be created using a <xref:System.Windows.Media.PathGeometry> or <xref:System.Windows.Media.StreamGeometry>. For more information, see the [Geometry Overview](geometry-overview.md).  \n  \n## See also\n\n- [Geometry Overview](geometry-overview.md)\n- [Create a Composite Shape](how-to-create-a-composite-shape.md)\n- [Create a Shape by Using a PathGeometry](how-to-create-a-shape-by-using-a-pathgeometry.md)\n","nodes":[{"pos":[4,210],"embed":true,"restype":"x-metadata","content":"title: \"How to: Create a Line Using a LineGeometry\"\nms.date: \"03/30/2017\"\ndev_langs: \n  - \"csharp\"\n  - \"vb\"\nhelpviewer_keywords: \n  - \"graphics [WPF], lines\"\nms.assetid: 41231b22-1f74-4c26-a8e7-a55b29f8f6bd","nodes":[{"content":"How to: Create a Line Using a LineGeometry","nodes":[{"pos":[0,42],"content":"How to: Create a Line Using a LineGeometry","nodes":[{"content":"How to: Create a Line Using a LineGeometry","pos":[0,42]}]}],"path":["title"],"nosxs":false}],"yml":true},{"pos":[217,259],"content":"How to: Create a Line Using a LineGeometry","linkify":"How to: Create a Line Using a LineGeometry","nodes":[{"content":"How to: Create a Line Using a LineGeometry","pos":[0,42]}]},{"content":"This example shows how to use the <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.LineGeometry&gt;</ph> class to describe a line.","pos":[260,360],"source":"This example shows how to use the <xref:System.Windows.Media.LineGeometry> class to describe a line."},{"content":"A <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.LineGeometry&gt;</ph> is defined by its start and end points.","pos":[361,443],"source":" A <xref:System.Windows.Media.LineGeometry> is defined by its start and end points."},{"pos":[452,459],"content":"Example","linkify":"Example","nodes":[{"content":"Example","pos":[0,7]}]},{"content":"The following example shows how to create and render a <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.LineGeometry&gt;</ph>.","pos":[463,559],"source":"The following example shows how to create and render a <xref:System.Windows.Media.LineGeometry>."},{"content":"A <ph